portant is knowing the base temperature (\"T_base\") since this value can be different in different usages, even for the same type of organism. <\/p>\n","answer_id":1277,"question_id":1272,"up_vote_count":6}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1272/why-dont-growing-degree-days-have-units-of-degrees-celsius-or-do-they","last_activity_date":1351066790,"creation_date":1330628229,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why dont \"growing degree days\" have units of degrees Celsius (or do they)?","body":"<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Growing-degree_day\" rel=\"nofollow\">From Wikipedia<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Growing degree days (GDD), also called growing degree units (GDUs), are a heuristic tool in phenology. GDD are a measure of heat accumulation used by horticulturists, gardeners, and farmers to predict plant and pest development rates such as the date that a flower will bloom or a crop reach maturity.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>GDD is calculated as $\\frac{T_{min}-T_{max}}{2}- T_{base}$ - so a quick check of the units would indicate that they are in the same units as T, i.e., degrees C. However, they are usually presented without units.<\/p>\n\n<p>Why is this?<\/p>\n","question_id":1272,"tags":["plant-physiology"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":247,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1351066790},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/52bddd6ae812be4933dc7d26c41d96af?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":154,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/154/abe","reputation":446,"display_name":"Abe","accept_rate":67},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":2626,"edited":false,"creation_date":1339743771,"comment_id":3