y look this up for your species or a similar one.<\/li>\n<li>Windspeed<\/li>\n<li>Characteristic dimension of leaves - measure, or look up a value for your species (Use this with windspeed to calculate boundary layer heat conductance).<\/li>\n<li>Leaf vapor conductance - a combination of stomatal and boundary layer conductance to water vapor. You must know something about where the stomata are on your leaf (both sides or one side), but you can often look this value up for a given species.<\/li>\n<li>A few other constants that are easy to look up.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>That's about it - its a somewhat hairy calculation, but if you have standard weather data and a little knowledge of the plants you are estimating the leaf temperature of, it should be manageable.<\/p>\n\n<p>This equation and other relevant info are in <a href=\"http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/0387949372\" rel=\"nofollow\">this book<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Campbell, G.S. and Norman, J.M. <em>An Introduction to Environmental Biophysics<\/em>. Springer Science, 1998<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":2757,"question_id":2626,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1340747735}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2626/can-i-estimate-leaf-temperature-from-air-temperature-what-other-information-wou","last_activity_date":1351064035,"creation_date":1339683264,"answer_count":1,"title":"Can I estimate leaf temperature from air temperature? What other information would be required?","body":"<p>Physiological measurements such as respiration rate and assimilation rate depend on temperature. <\/p>\n\n<p>Most papers report tissue temperature (e.g. leaf temperature for leaf measurements), although some report air temperature.<\/p>\n\n<p>My goal is to compare measurements in the literature.  I use leaf temperature at time of measurement to adjust the rates to a common temperature. Currently, I assume that if leaf temperature is not available, it is the same as air temperature. (This is often assumed in papers where the leaf temperature was not measured).<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there a way to estimate the difference between air temperature and leaf temperature? I can get fairly good estimates of other physiological traits (e.g. leaf thickness, albedo, stomatal conductance) as well as climate data (e.g. humidity, soil moisture content).<\/p>\n\n<p>My model is:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>$T_{leaf} = T_a + X + \\epsilon$<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>And I currently assume X = 0 in my calculations<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there a better way to estimate X?<\/p>\n\n<p>Under what conditions would X &lt; 0? X > 0?<\/p>\n","question_id":2626,"tags":["physiology","plant-physiology","photosynthesis","ecophysiology"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":2757,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":558,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1351064035},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"closed_date":1351033814,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":2,"post_id":4983,"edited":false,"creation_date":1350924346,"comment_id":7064,"body":"Could you expand on your question a bit please? I cannot understand what you are asking here."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a43651dba3f306d9c0c0b92a7457722?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1441,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1441/bitwise","reputation":1705,"display_name":"Bitwise"},"score":0,"post_id":4983,"edited":false,"creation_date":1350931106,"comment_id":7065,"body":"self-preservation in what sense?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.grava