ow\">paper<\/a> describes the structural changes induced in human pancreatic lipase by lowering the pH. The secondary structure of the enzyme is stable within a pH range of 3.0 to 6.5. At this pH, a reversible opening of the lid controlling the access to the active site was observed. So, there is another aspect of activation - pH and the ability to open the enzyme lid so that the fat molecule enters the active site.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1516,"question_id":1492,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1350390343}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1492/what-conditions-are-necessary-for-hpl-human-pancreatic-lipase-to-activate","last_activity_date":1350390343,"creation_date":1332177312,"answer_count":1,"title":"What conditions are necessary for HPL (human pancreatic lipase) to activate?","body":"<p>What conditions are necessary for human pancreatic lipase to activate? Is there an optimal temperature or pH? How quickly does it take effect?<\/p>\n","question_id":1492,"tags":["human-biology","enzymes"],"score":8,"accepted_answer_id":1516,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":816,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1332440307},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dcf6930be341756f92ff4dad89d37342?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":152,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/152/christian","reputation":1037,"display_name":"Christian","accept_rate":62},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24c0e23c30888c23e2d4fe9991cf2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":57,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/57/jonsca","reputation":3367,"display_name":"jonsca","accept_rate":100},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dcf6930be341756f92ff4dad89d37342?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":152,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/152/christian","reputation":103