 source of this quote?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/75ac58e3e0106650994b315a6ad4c525?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":103,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/103/inquilinekea","reputation":1084,"display_name":"InquilineKea","accept_rate":52},"score":0,"post_id":798,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1327549093,"comment_id":936,"body":"Wikipedia (have added a note for clarification)."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3cfeec7dfb47b3d98c5edf17295e959b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":81,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/81/poshpaws","reputation":4731,"display_name":"Poshpaws","accept_rate":71},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1349959188,"creation_date":1347980286,"body":"<p><a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/%20doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0019194\" rel=\"nofollow\">This study<\/a> found a statistically significant decline in NAD+:NADH ratios and in intracellular NAD+ with age in the organs of rats. <\/p>\n\n<p>They discuss that the activation of  PARP - the  NAD-dependent enzyme Poly(ADP-ribose) polymerase-1 instrumental in DNA repair - increases in aging organs (heart, liver, kidneys). This depletes cellular NAD+ levels via poly(ADP-ribosylation) of proteins. This reduced cellular  NAD+ then reduces the effectiveness of Sirtuins (Sirt1) which can <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12220851\" rel=\"nofollow\">deacetylate tumor-suppressor proteins such as p53.<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Here's schematic showing the basic idea from their figure 10:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/mp6zF.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>So, the inference is that oxidative stress in vertebrates increases with age due to lowered cellular NAD+ - i.e.,  consistent with the free-radical theory of aging.  This could mean that lowered cellular NAD+, NAD+/NADH in any given individual may well decrease said individuals lifespan.<\/p>\n\n<p>The authors of the first study (Braidy et al 2011) suggest that therapies involved in maintaining high NAD+ levels may alleviate age-associated disorders.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/%20doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0019194\" rel=\"nofollow\">Braidy N, Guillemin GJ, Mansour H, Chan-Ling T, Poljak A, et al. (2011) Age Related Changes in NAD+ Metabolism Oxidative Stress and Sirt1 Activity in Wistar Rats. PLoS ONE 6(4)<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12220851\" rel=\"nofollow\">Smith, J., (2002) Human Sir2 and the 'silencing' of p53 activity, Traneds, Cell Biol. 12, 404<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":3583,"question_id":798,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1349959188}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/798/how-does-the-nad-nadh-ratio-affect-lifespan-in-vertebrates","last_activity_date":1349959188,"creation_date":1327436368,"answer_count":1,"title":"How does the NAD+/NADH ratio affect lifespan in vertebrates?","body":"<p>Here's the proximate physical implication of the ratio (from the Wikipedia article on NADH).<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The balance between the oxidized and reduced forms of nicotinamide\n  adenine dinucleotide is called the NAD+/NADH ratio. This ratio is an\n  important component of what is called the redox state of a cell, a\n  measurement that reflects both the metabolic activities and the health\n  of cells. The effects of the NAD+/NADH ratio are complex,\n  controlling the activity of several key enzymes, including\n  glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase and pyruvate dehydrogenase.\n  In healthy mammalian tissues, estimates of the ratio between free NAD+\n  and NADH in the cytoplasm typically lie around 700; the ratio is thus\n  favourable for oxidative reactions. The ratio of total\n  NAD+/NADH is much lower, with estimates ranging from 0.05 to 4. In\n  contrast, the NADP+/NADPH ratio is normally about 0.005, so NADPH is\n  the dominant form of this coenzyme. These different ratios are key\n  to the different metabolic roles of NADH and NADPH.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>So here's my question: how does this manifest in vertebrate aging? Is it something that's simply the resultant of other aging processes, or can the ratio also contribute to aging in a certain way?<\/p>\n","question_id":798,"tags":["senescence"],"score":8,"accepted_answer_id":3583,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":4456,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1327593762},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":0,"post_id":1777,"edited":false,"creation_date":1334274867,"comment_id":2318,"body":"Question has been reasked at <a href=\"http://www.biostars.org/post/show/42502/how-do-i-prepare-a-pdb-for-submission-to-the-protein-data-bank/\" rel=\"nofollow\">biostars.org/post/show/42502/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/69dcd277799bf98a2cd1c39dc48a82a3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4533,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4533/marcin","reputation":156,"display_name":"marcin"},"score":0,"post_id":1777,"edited":false,"creation_date":1444990622,"comment_id":66466,"body":"If yo