r.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><em>Are those unicellular dykaria secondary unicellular or not? Given that the both branches of dykaria show similarities in fruiting bodies, it seems to be plausible that the common ancestors of dykaria had a similar structure.<\/em><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I am not exactly aware of the similarities in fruiting bodies in both branches, but if the physiology behind fruiting bodies are similar, it is <strong>very likely<\/strong> because the dikaryan common ancestor had a similar mechanism.<\/p>\n","answer_id":3882,"question_id":3873,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1349888254}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/3873/do-all-mushrooms-have-the-same-multicellular-ancestor","last_activity_date":1349888254,"creation_date":1349818141,"answer_count":1,"title":"Do all mushrooms have the same multicellular ancestor?","body":"<p>Do all mushrooms have the same multicellular ancestor? Did that ancestor feature common mushroom elements such as cap, stem, sporofore, vulva, bulb, etc.<\/p>\n","question_id":3873,"tags":["mycology"],"score":6,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":364,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/35114dfb827dc71cb3a8ff281617c5b8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":535,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/535/larry-parnell","reputation":3430,"display_name":"Larry_Parnell"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1349872817,"creation_date":1349872817,"body":"<p>With high(er) temperatures, especially in drier air with a bit of breeze, a plant will transpire more. While not a chemical solution, it is indeed a 